=========================================================
join(), detach(), joinable() (C++ INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

---------------------------------------------------------
1. join()
---------------------------------------------------------

Definition
----------

join() waits for the thread to finish execution.

The calling thread (usually main) blocks until the worker thread completes.

Syntax
------

t.join();

Example

#include <thread>
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void task()
{
    cout << "Thread running\n";
}

int main()
{
    thread t(task);

    t.join();      // Wait for thread

    cout << "Main exits\n";
}

Output

Thread running
Main exits

Interview Points

✓ Waits for thread completion.
✓ Synchronizes the main thread with the worker thread.
✓ Can be called only once.

---------------------------------------------------------

2. detach()
---------------------------------------------------------

Definition
----------

detach() separates the thread from the thread object.

The thread continues running independently.

The main thread does NOT wait for it.

Syntax
------

t.detach();

Example

thread t(task);

t.detach();

cout << "Main exits\n";

Interview Points

✓ Runs independently.
✓ No synchronization with main thread.
✓ Resources are released automatically after completion.
✓ Use only when the thread doesn't need to communicate results back.

---------------------------------------------------------

3. joinable()
---------------------------------------------------------

Definition
----------

joinable() checks whether a thread can be joined or detached.

Syntax
------

if(t.joinable())
{
    t.join();
}

Returns

true  → Thread is active and can be joined/detached.

false → Thread has already been joined, detached, or was never assigned.

---------------------------------------------------------

Example

thread t(task);

if(t.joinable())
{
    t.join();
}

---------------------------------------------------------

Comparison

| join() | detach() |
|---------|----------|
| Waits for thread | Doesn't wait |
| Synchronizes threads | Runs independently |
| Main blocks | Main continues immediately |
| Use when result is needed | Use for background tasks |

---------------------------------------------------------

Important Rule

Every std::thread must be either:

✓ join()

OR

✓ detach()

before the thread object is destroyed.

Otherwise the program calls std::terminate().

---------------------------------------------------------

One-line Interview Answers

join():
"join() blocks the calling thread until the target thread finishes execution."

detach():
"detach() allows a thread to run independently without waiting for its completion."

joinable():
"joinable() checks whether a thread can still be joined or detached."

---------------------------------------------------------

Memory Trick

join()      → Wait
detach()    → Don't Wait
joinable()  → Can I join/detach?
